url: "https://github.com/Buchiexplores/llm-memory-eval"
abstract: >-
  llm-memory-eval is an open-source Python package that operationalizes a
  comparative, repeated-measures evaluation of Summarization-Based Memory
  (recursive abstractive summarization performed by the base large language
  model) and Retrieval-Augmented Generation (dense embeddings with FAISS over
  chunked context) for long-term conversational performance, on three
  long-context benchmarks (LongBench, LoCoMo, and LongMemEval). The harness
  provides config-driven, backend-agnostic inference (Ollama, Together AI, AWS
  Bedrock, Hugging Face Inference Endpoints, and any OpenAI-compatible
  endpoint), deterministic decoding controls, and a complete statistical
  pipeline (paired-samples t-tests with Holm-Bonferroni correction, Wilcoxon
  signed-rank confirmatory tests, two-way ANOVA on Strategy x Conversation
  Length with Bonferroni-corrected simple effects, Shapiro-Wilk and Levene
  assumption diagnostics, Cohen's d, and partial eta-squared) that reproduces
  the quantitative results reported in the associated doctoral dissertation.
keywords:
  - large language models
  - retrieval-augmented generation
  - summarization-based memory
  - long-context evaluation
  - long-term conversational memory
  - LongBench
  - LoCoMo
  - LongMemEval
  - reproducible research
  - distributed cognition
  - cognitive load theory
